This is a brief tutorial on how to use R and the ggplot2 package to plot basic supply and demand charts. A more comprehensive guide to ggplot2, created by RStudio, is provided here.

Installing Things

This method requires an installation of R and the R package ggplot2. ggplot2 is a flexible, user-written graphics package for R. RStudio, an integrated development environment (IDE), is highly recommended but not technically necessary. If you dont have any of this on your computer currently, these are the steps I would use:

  1. Download and install R from a CRAN repository.
  2. Download and install RStudio from the RStudio website.
  3. Once youve installed both R and RStudio, open the RStudio application.
  4. Install the ggplot2 package by typing this command directly into the console (bottom-right panel by default):
install.packages("ggplot2", dependencies = TRUE)

This is all youll need to make the plots.

The RStudio Environment

A little about RStudio and its four-pane set-up.

  1. Script Editor (Top-Left): This is akin to Statas do-file editor. You can open a new script by clicking on the icon with a green plus on it.
  2. Console (Bottom-Left): This is the actual R session that is running. You can interact with it directly and is akin to typing directly into Stata. Without RStudio, this would be the only window you would see when running Base R
  3. Environment (Top-Right): A listing of all the objects (data sets, vectors, matrices, etc.) that are active in your session. This is not as important.
  4. Files/Plots/Packages (Bottom-RIght): This is a catch-all pane, but most important for our purposes, it will be where previews of your graphs will appear.

Making Plots

To use ggplot2, we need to first load the package. This is a distinction between R and Stata: whereas user-written commands in Stata are always available once installed, you need to load them for every R session you start. You can do so by using the library command.

library(ggplot2)

If this doesnt produce any error messages, the package is successfully loaded.

Setting up the Plot Environment

Next, we want to set up our plotting environment. This is the most difficult part of this process. We initialize a plot by using the ggplot() command:

ggplot()

This produces a blank space for our plot. Usually, we make graphs from pre-existing data and graphics programs sensibly determine the coordinates of the graphing space for us. This exercise is a little different in that were free-drawing these curves. The next step then is to set up X and Y axes and arbitrarily have the X and Y axes both run from 0 to 200.

ggplot()+
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200))

The logic of ggplot2 is that you build graphics by continually layering on different components. This principle is the greatest strength of ggplot2: it lets each layer be as dependent or independent as you would like. Each of these layers is represented by a different line of the above command:

  1. a base layer = ggplot()
  2. an X axis titled Quantity that spans from 0 to 200 = scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200))
  3. a Y axis titled Price that spans from 0 to 200 = scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200))

Notice that each parentheses are opened and closed out for each layer and the layers are linked together using +. Unlike Stata, R does not use carraige returns as delimiters, so the spaces between the layers are for the sake of visual clarity only.

If you want change the titles of the axes or adjust the limits of the axes, you can do so by adjusting the values of the options of scale_x_continuous and scale_y_continuous:

ggplot()+
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Some X Variable", limits=c(-100,100)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Some Y Variable", limits=c(-100,100))

There are other aesthetics that you can control. If you want to specify the increments of the axes, you can do that by specifying breaks option. For example, lets say I want to specify that the X axis goes by increments of 10:

ggplot()+
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), breaks=seq(0,200,10)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200))

You can write out the breaks option completely like this:

breaks=c(0,10, 20, 30, 40, 50, ... ,200)

But I use the seq function as a shortcut above, which produces a vector of numbers ranging from 0 to 200 in increments of 10.

For the purposes of this tutorial, I am okay with the default axis increments but I want three aesthetic adjustments:

  1. A clean black and white look. I can get this by adding the theme_bw() layer. For aesthetic reasons, I want the default font size to be 8 within this theme.
  2. I want to remove the grid lines inside the plot. Ill use the panel.grid options inside of a theme layer.
  3. Get rid of the overhang around the axes to make the axes cut off exactly and 0 and 200. I can get this by specifying the expand option within scale_x_continuous and scale_y_continuous.

All together, the base plot for these supply and demand graphics that Ill use in this tutorial looks like this:

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme with default font size = 8
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) #set up y-axis

Lines (Supply and Demand Curves)

This is the easier part. Once we have our plot background set, we just layer different types of plots (these are called geoms in ggplot speak) on top of our background. To draw lines where we have a defined intercept and slope, we use geom_abline. Lets use the supply and demand curves from our last homework, re-arranged so that price is the y variable:

\[\begin{aligned} P &= 175 - Q^D \\ P &= 100 + 2Q^S \end{aligned}\]

geom_abline requires that we give it a value for intercept and slope, which we have from our equations. To add these lines, we simply layer them over our background.

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100) ## supply curve

The basics of our plot are now in place. If we want to annotate the graphs, we can do so by adding in an annotate layer. The annotate layer will ask for the type of annotation you want (text), x and y coordinates, and what you want the annotation to say (label). You can also adjust the size of the annotation by specifying a size value.

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) ##supply curve annotation

Adding new lines is as simple as layering on new geoms. For instance, if we want to add a new supply curve that is shifted out due to an increase in production, defined as \(P= 70 + 2Q^S\):

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 70)+ ## supply curve 1
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  annotate("text", x = 60, y = 175, label = "S1", size = 3) ##supply curve 1 annotation

If we want to make this new supply curve look different, we can specify a linetype and/or a color:

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 70, linetype = "dotted", color = "blue")+ ## supply curve 1
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  annotate("text", x = 60, y = 175, label = "S1", size = 3) ##supply curve 1 annotation

Two nots about colors and line types:

  1. Changing the color of lines/borders involves changing the color parameter. Changing the color of bars and regions involves changing the fill parameter. If you try to use color to change the color of a bar or region, only the border will change colors.
  2. A list of R colors can be found here. A list of R line types can be found here

Line Segments (Equilibrium Values and Tax Regions)

Line segments are useful for marking equilibrium points and tax regions. We can draw these by using the geom_segment layer; geom_segment differs from geom_abline in that you can define an end point of the line. This geom requires that you provide starting and ending points for the x and y coordinates. For instance, the equilibrium quantities for the original supply and demand curves are \(Q=150\) and \(P=25\). We want horizontal and vertical lines to mark these values:

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 70)+ ## supply curve 1
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  annotate("text", x = 60, y = 175, label = "S1", size = 3) + ##supply curve 1 annotation 
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed") ## equlibrium price 0

For the vertical line, depicting the equilibrium quantity, we want the x value to be fixed, therefore both x and xend = 25, but we want the y to range from the origin y=0 to the equilibrium point yend=150. The same logic is applied to drawing the horizontal price line.

Shaded Areas (Total Value)

What if we want to shade in certain areas? This can be done using the geom_rect layer for rectangles or the more generic geom_ribbon layer any shape. Returning to the homework questions, what happens if we impose a 30 dollar tax on each unit? We can use the line segments above to denote the tax region and the post-tax equilibrium quantity.

ggplot()+
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=130, yend=130), linetype = "dotted")+ ## sellers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=160, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## buyers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=15 , xend=15, y=0, yend=160), linetype = "dotted") ## equilibrium quantity + tax

If we want to shade in the rectangular region that represents tax revenue, we can use the geom_rect layer:

ggplot()+
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=130, yend=130), linetype = "dotted")+ ## sellers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=160, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## buyers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=15 , xend=15, y=0, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## equilibrium quantity + tax
  geom_rect(aes(xmin=0,xmax=15,ymin=130,ymax=160), color ="gray") ## tax revenue

Here we see that the order of our layers matters. Because geom_rect is the last layer it sits on top of everything below it. If we wanted the underlying lines to show through, we can move geom_rect earlier in layer order:

ggplot()+
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  geom_rect(aes(xmin=0,xmax=15,ymin=130,ymax=160), color ="gray") + ##tax revenue
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=130, yend=130), linetype = "dotted")+ ## sellers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=160, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## buyers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=15 , xend=15, y=0, yend=160), linetype = "dotted") ## equilibrium quantity + tax

Or, if wes simply want to adjust the transparency of the shaded region, we can adjust the alpha parameter, which permits values ranging from 0 (see-through) to 1 (opaque)

ggplot()+
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=130, yend=130), linetype = "dotted")+ ## sellers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=160, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## buyers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=15 , xend=15, y=0, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## equilibrium quantity + tax
  geom_rect(aes(xmin=0,xmax=15,ymin=130,ymax=160), fill ="gray", alpha = .5) ## tax revenue

Instead of shading in the tax revenue region, what if we want to instead shade in the triangular region representing deadweight loss? Shading in non-rectangular regions is somewhat more difficult and requires the use of the more flexible, but less intuitive, geom_ribbon layer.

ggplot()+
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=130, yend=130), linetype = "dotted")+ ## sellers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=15, y=160, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## buyers price
  geom_segment(aes(x=15 , xend=15, y=0, yend=160), linetype = "dotted")+ ## equilibrium quantity + tax
  geom_ribbon(aes(x=c(15,25),ymin=c(130,150),ymax=c(160,150)), fill="gray", alpha="0.5")

geom_region requires a span of values that are not intuitively labeled. In general, fill in the values from left to right. x=c(15,25) indicates that you want your shaded region to extend from x = 15 to x = 25. ymin=c(130,150) are the y coordinates for the lower side of the triangle to span from y = 130 to y = 150. Lastly, ymax=c(160,150) are the y coordinates for the upper side of the triangle to span from y = 160 to y = 150. In the case of a triangle, you can swap the values of ymin and ymax and produce the same shaded region.

Total Value Under Curve Example

For another example, what if we want to shade in the regions depicting the social value to an increase in supply? Returning to our plot that included the new, shifted-out supply curve, we can shade in the areas representing the two sources of social value:

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 70)+ ## supply curve 1
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  annotate("text", x = 60, y = 175, label = "S1", size = 3) + ##supply curve 1 annotation
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=35 , xend=35, y=0, yend=140), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 1
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=35, y=140, yend=140), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 1
  geom_ribbon(aes(x=c(20,25),ymin=0,ymax=c(140,150)), fill="gray", alpha="0.5") + ## value due to freed resources
  geom_ribbon(aes(x=c(25,35),ymin=0,ymax=c(150,140)), fill="gray", alpha="0.9") ## value due to increased production

The value of freed resources (the lighter gray region) is a shaded region running from x= 20 (left) to x = 25 (right), a minimum y ranging from y = 0 (left) to y = 0 (right) and a maximum y ranging from y = 140 (left) to y = 150 (right). The same logic applies to the region depicting value of increased quantity (the darker gray region), only now, the maximum y ranges from y = 150 (left) to y = 140 (right).

Exporting Plots

Once youve created your graph, how do you export it? The easiest option would be to screenshot the graph, but the image quality can be low. Above the Plots pane of RStudio, there is an Export button that works but I have found it to work inconsistently. The best option is to incorpporate a line of code that exports it for you, giving you a full range of export options. Taking our last graph, we can use the command ggsave to produce a pdf called totalvalue.pdf.

# set working directory
setwd("~/projects")

ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 70)+ ## supply curve 1
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  annotate("text", x = 60, y = 175, label = "S1", size = 3) + ##supply curve 1 annotation
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=35 , xend=35, y=0, yend=140), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 1
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=35, y=140, yend=140), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 1
  geom_ribbon(aes(x=c(20,25),ymin=0,ymax=c(140,150)), fill="gray", alpha="0.5") + ## value due to freed resources
  geom_ribbon(aes(x=c(25,35),ymin=0,ymax=c(150,140)), fill="gray", alpha="0.9") ## value due to increased production

### Save this plot
ggsave(filename = "totalvalue.pdf")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

ggsave has smart defaults and only requires 1 parameter, filename, which provides the name and format of the exported image. By default, ggsave will export the last produced graph. If you do not want this to be the case, you need to (1) name your plots using the <- operator and (2) specify the plot parameter.

myplot <- ggplot()+ #set up plot space
  theme_bw(base_size=8)+ #black and white theme 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())+ #remove grid lines
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Quantity", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0)) +  #set up x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Price", limits=c(0,200), expand=c(0,0))+ #set up y-axis
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 175)+ ## demand curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 100)+ ## supply curve 0
  geom_abline(slope = 2, intercept = 70)+ ## supply curve 1
  annotate("text", x = 175, y = 25, label = "D0", size = 3) + ##demand curve 0 annotation
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 175, label = "S0", size = 3) + ##supply curve 0 annotation 
  annotate("text", x = 60, y = 175, label = "S1", size = 3) + ##supply curve 1 annotation
  geom_segment(aes(x=25 , xend=25, y=0, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=25, y=150, yend=150), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 0
  geom_segment(aes(x=35 , xend=35, y=0, yend=140), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equilibrium quantity 1
  geom_segment(aes(x=0 , xend=35, y=140, yend=140), linetype = "dashed")+ ## equlibrium price 1
  geom_ribbon(aes(x=c(20,25),ymin=0,ymax=c(140,150)), fill="gray", alpha="0.5") + ## value due to freed resources
  geom_ribbon(aes(x=c(25,35),ymin=0,ymax=c(150,140)), fill="gray", alpha="0.9") ## value due to increased production

### Save this plot
setwd("~/projects")
ggsave(filename = "totalvalue.pdf", plot = myplot)
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

ggsave will try to export a plot that resembles the size of the plot in your RStudio Plots pane. If you make the pane bigger and re-run the ggsave command, it will make a bigger plot. If you would rather manually specify the size of the exported plot, you can fill out the height and width parameters:

ggsave(filename = "totalvalue_1.pdf", plot = myplot, height = 8, width = 8)

One very annoying thing about changing the size of the figure on export is that text will not change proportionally. Therefore, you will need to play with the text size of your plot in order for it to be sized appropriately on the exported image.

Conclusion

The various graphs above, along with some dedictated Google searching, should be enough to provide a recipe for producing basic supply and demand graphs.
